## 1. Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)

In EME-GIR, a Class is defined as an **`E_2`** (literally, a "House" or "Temple estate"). A House contains its own properties (tribute) and methods (servants).

To instantiate an object, we use the `{lu}` (Person) determinative, because objects are active agents that perform tasks.

Here is how we define a `Merchant` class that can track inventory and make trades:

```
// Define the House of the Merchant
E_2 Merchant {
    
    // Properties (State)
    {im} name;
    {ninda} silver;
    {šam} inventory; // Array of goods

    // The Constructor (The Founding of the House)
    ki-ĝal_2( {im} mu, {ninda} k_3 ) {
        name =ba mu;
        silver =ba k_3;
        inventory =ba [];
    }

    // A Method to buy goods
    mu-na-ru( {im} item, {ninda} cost ) {
        tukum-bi (silver >= cost) {
            silver =ba silver - cost;
            inventory.bi-si(item); // bi-si = "to pack into/append"
        }
        ni-ĝen; // Returns "this" object state
    }
}

// --- Instantiating and Using the Object ---
// Construct a new merchant named Ur-Namma with 100 silver pieces
{lu} ur_namma =ba lu-ga.Merchant("Ur-Namma", 100);

// Ur-Namma buys "Lapislazuli" for 30 silver
ur_namma.mu-na-ru("Lapislazuli", 30);

```

