## 2. Asynchronous Operations & Event Listening

Complex modern programs can't just pause while waiting for a server request or a database read. Sumerian has the perfect grammatical structure for this: the **Infix of Waiting/Anticipation (`-m-`)**.

In EME-GIR, asynchronous functions are prefixed with **`ba-m-`**, which tells the compiler, *"Allocate a background thread and yield until the clay tablet arrives."*

```
// Fetching data from a remote temple ledger (API Call)
ba-m-ka_9( {im} temple_url ) {
    // The compiler pauses this block, waiting for a network handshake
    {im} data =ba mu-un-de_6(temple_url); // mu-un-de_6 = "to bring from afar"
    
    // Resolving a Promise / Callback
    ni-zu (data) {
        data.ibĝare; // Print the fetched data when it arrives
    }
}

```

