## 3. Recursion: The Infinite Descent

To handle complex math, algorithms (like sorting), or tree structures, a language must support recursion. Sumerian handles recursion beautifully through the concept of the **`BALA`** (the cycle, or rotation of office).

Here is a complex algorithm—the **Fibonacci Sequence**—written in recursively structured EME-GIR:

```
// Recursive function to calculate the Nth Fibonacci number
bala-ĝiri_3( {ninda} n ) {
    
    // Base Case 1: If n is 0, return 0
    tukum-bi (n == 0) {
        gur_ud 0; // gur_ud = "to return / turn back"
    }
    
    // Base Case 2: If n is 1, return 1
    tukum-bi (n == 1) {
        gur_ud 1;
    }

    // Recursive Step: bala-ĝiri_3(n-1) + bala-ĝiri_3(n-2)
    {ninda} step_1 =ba bala-ĝiri_3(n - 1);
    {ninda} step_2 =ba bala-ĝiri_3(n - 2);

    gur_ud (step_1 + step_2);
}

```

